# How to Plan the Perfect Group Outing at Infusion Play Victoria in 2026

You've got a group. You need a plan. And you're done with the same old dinner-and-drinks routine.

Whether you're organising a birthday, a corporate team day, a family afternoon, or just a crew of friends who want to do something worth talking about, Infusion Play at 546 Yates St in Downtown Victoria has you covered. Physical challenges, free-roaming VR, claw machines, handmade food and drinks — all under one roof, no car required.

Here's how to make the most of it.

## Decide What Kind of Group You're Bringing

Knowing your crowd upfront makes the whole visit smoother. Not every group wants the same thing, and Infusion Play has enough variety that the right mix matters.

### Corporate Groups and Team Events

Bring the whole team. The combination of competitive physical challenges and co-op VR creates moments for genuine connection that a restaurant or bowling alley just can't replicate.

The laser maze gets people moving and laughing fast. The VR Arena — running titles like After the Fall and Arizona Sunshine — drops your team into a multiplayer zombie shooter where you physically move through the space and actually have to communicate to survive. Layer in the points-based reward system from Interactive Play, and you've got built-in competition with something real at stake.

The on-site food and beverage menu — bubble tea, ice cream, Bingsu — means you don't need to split the group across two venues. Eat, play, and celebrate in one spot.

For groups of 30 or more, book in advance. Spaces fill up, and showing up with 20 colleagues to find the VR Arena fully booked is not the vibe.

### Families with Kids

The venue works well for mixed-age families, with one important note: the Interactive Play rooms and VR Arena are best suited for kids aged 8 and up. For younger children under 8, the sister location Infusion XR Arcade is the better fit — it runs room-scale VR titles including Elven Assassin archery and Mini Golf in a format built for smaller guests.

For families with kids in the 8-to-14 range, start at the claw machine lounge. It's lower intensity, easy to enjoy at any age, and keeps everyone occupied while the group gets settled. Then move into the laser maze and the VR Arena for a full session that covers physical and digital play without anyone getting left out.

### Couples

Skip the movie. The Challenge + Immersion bundle gives you and your partner a two-hour experience that's equal parts physical and immersive — dodge lasers, then grab a rifle and survive the zombie apocalypse together. Light competition between two people makes for a genuinely fun date dynamic, and the shared story you walk away with beats anything on a streaming service.

Grab a bubble tea or Bingsu after your session. Done.

### Friend Groups and Spontaneous Visits

Walk-ins are welcome. If your Saturday plan fell through and someone says "let's just go somewhere," Infusion Play works without a reservation. That said, if you know you're coming, booking online at infusion-play.com locks in your spot and saves you the wait.

## Choose Your Experiences

Three formats. Do one, or stack them.

### The VR Arena

Grab a rifle-style controller and step into free-roaming VR. After the Fall and Arizona Sunshine are both multiplayer zombie shooters where you physically move through the space — no sitting, no standing in place. You run, aim, reload, and react.

This is not the VR you tried at a mall kiosk in 2019. The free-roaming format and full-body controllers make it a different physical experience entirely. Check the VR Arena page at infusion-play.com/vrarena to see what's running.

### Interactive Play

Run the laser maze. Solve spot-the-difference challenges. Play Charades under pressure. The Interactive Play rooms mix physical challenges with mind-based games, and every session feeds into a points total you can redeem for rewards at the end.

This format is great for groups because it creates natural competition. Someone always surprises you in the laser maze. Head to the Interactive Play page at infusion-play.com/interactiveplay for the full breakdown.

### Claw Machines and the Lounge

Not every moment of a group outing needs to be high intensity. The claw machine arcade lounge is where you decompress, grab a drink, and try your luck. It's the only claw machine setup in Downtown Victoria — a genuinely fun way to wind down between bigger activities or keep younger kids busy while the rest of the group finishes a VR session.

### The Challenge + Immersion Bundle

Want the full Infusion Play experience in a single booking? This is it. VR and physical challenge play combined, so you're not choosing one or the other. Full pricing details live on the Pricing and Booking page at infusion-play.com/book-online.

## Practical Planning Tips

Book ahead for groups of 6 or more. Walk-ins are welcome, but the venue fills up — especially on weekends and evenings. Booking online locks in your time slot and makes arrival faster for everyone.

Wear comfortable clothes. You will run, jump, and dodge in the Interactive Play rooms. Leave the dress shoes at home.

Budget your time. A full Challenge + Immersion session runs roughly one to two hours. Add claw machine time and food, and you're looking at a solid two-to-three-hour outing without anyone checking their phone.

Getting there is easy. The venue is at 546 Yates St in the heart of Downtown Victoria, near Ferris' Bar and Leopold's Tavern. No car needed — it's walkable from most hotels and central areas.

Arrive a few minutes early. Especially with a larger group. Getting everyone briefed before your session starts means you use every minute of your booked time.

